:::summary
Catholic philosophy is the rich and rigorous intellectual tradition of the Catholic Church — a centuries-long project of bringing the tools of Greek reason into dialogue with divine revelation to produce a unified account of reality, knowledge, morality, and God. From the patristic era through the golden age of Scholasticism and down to the present, Catholic thinkers have insisted that faith and reason are not enemies but complementary paths to truth: "faith seeking understanding," in Anselm's famous phrase. This tradition produced some of the greatest works of philosophy and theology ever written, above all the *Summa Theologiae* of Thomas Aquinas.
:::

